URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS722779769	2020-05-06 05:45:36	1048	species	Chestnut Wood-Quail	Odontophorus hyperythrus			X					Colombia	CO	Antioquia	CO-ANT							Arrierito Antioqueño ProAves Reserve	L603931	H	6.9887752	-75.1202202	2012-03-27		obsr38671	S24584150	Historical	P62	EBIRD				4	1	G4253660	0	1	0			Heard	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS957333571	2020-07-20 16:15:54	1048	species	Chestnut Wood-Quail	Odontophorus hyperythrus			3					Colombia	CO	Antioquia	CO-ANT							Arrierito Antioqueño ProAves Reserve	L603931	H	6.9887752	-75.1202202	2012-05-21		obsr637980	S71571105	Historical	P62	EBIRD					0		0	1	0		We spent the whole day on the trails. As we walked up to the tower we managed to find a close Chestnut-capped Piha. We then managed brief but good views of a Multicolored Tanager from the tower. We continued on up to the ridge and managed great looks at a Tawny-throated Leaftosser and followed this up with a nice pair of Lanceolated Monklets. Several noisy Red-throated Caracaras showed well and birding along the ridge produced Purplish-mantled Tanager and Indigo Flowerpiercer. We also located a small group of adult and juvenile Blue-fronted Parrotlets which gave great views as they fed in the canopy.----In the late afternoon we returned to lower elevations spotting a small group of the endangered White-footed Tamarins on the way down. We returned to the seedfeeder and in the late afternoon a small group of Chestnut Wood-Quail were seen well as they made a brief visit. We returned to the lodge and finished the day enjoying further views of Colombian Chachalaca, with a small group visiting the fruit feeder in the garden.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS841704861	2020-02-03 15:37:35	1048	species	Chestnut Wood-Quail	Odontophorus hyperythrus			2					Colombia	CO	Caldas	CO-CAL							Reserva Ecológica Río Blanco	L2241379	H	5.0694879	-75.4413374	2019-12-24	06:50:00	obsr330147	S62591600	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	327	5.255		2	1	G4785230	1	1	0		This was one of my favorite bird walks in Colombia yet. So thankful for Daniel and Andrés for their warmth and patience in helping us see such cool birds and learn about the reserva. Standout moments, in no particular order: the antpitta feeding stations, including a momma antpitta calling for her little guy to join in on the worm feast; a fast-flying flock of tanagers flying over us and overwhelming our ID capabilities; sunrise catching the wings of rusty-faced parrots as we began our walk; the mixed flock at the top of the trail blowing us away in terms of colors and song; the gorgeous and devilish-looking stygian owl; stopping in the middle to play tejo at Daniel's house; doing playback for the treehunter. So cool!!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS492812604	2020-05-06 05:46:37	1048	species	Chestnut Wood-Quail	Odontophorus hyperythrus			1					Colombia	CO	Chocó	CO-CHO							Las Tangaras ProAves Reserve	L856448	H	5.8206127	-76.1726761	2012-05-31	05:00:00	obsr681234	S36445926	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	620	40.234		12	1		0	1	0		ABC Field Triip		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS957378958	2020-07-20 16:19:34	1048	species	Chestnut Wood-Quail	Odontophorus hyperythrus			X					Colombia	CO	Chocó	CO-CHO							Las Tangaras ProAves Reserve	L856448	H	5.8206127	-76.1726761	2012-05-24		obsr637980	S71574905	Historical	P62	EBIRD					1		0	1	0		We spent another day at Las Tangaras. We quickly located an Tatama Tapaculo (at the time a “new” species currently awaiting formal description), which showed well as did a couple of Yellow-collared Chlorophonias. A Yellow-breasted Antpitta was seen by some as it fed on the road and a Golden-headed Quetzal gave superb views at the start of the main trail. A pair of White-headed Wrens also showed very well and we enjoyed further views of many of the species seen on the previous day including Toucan Barbet, Tricoloured (Choco) Brush-Finch, Olivaceous Piha and Purple-bibbed Whitetip. A couple of Variegated Bristle-Tyrants and a Fulvous-breasted Flatbill were seen in mixed flocks and a couple of Yellow-Vented Woodpecker were much appreciated. We rounded the day off with another Yellow-breasted Antpitta that appeared on the road in the late afternoon and which was seen by those who had missed the earlier bird.	Heard only.
